-3
      " id=3D"section-step-1-find-the-median-of-the-data-q2">Step 1 - Find =
the median of the data (Q2)
</h4><p class=3D"text-grey col-span-10 md:col-span-8 lg:col-span-6 md:col-s=
tart-2 lg:col-start-3">To find the median (or Q2), arrange your data in asc=
ending order. If the number of data points you have is odd, the median will=
 be the middle value of your data. If you have an even number of data point=
s, the median will be the average of the two middle numbers in your data.
</p><h4 class=3D"
       =20
       =20
       =20
        font-light text-[20px] leading-[27px] md:text-[27px] md:leading-[36=
px]
       =20
        col-span-10 md:col-span-8 lg:col-span-6 md:col-start-2 lg:col-start=
-3
      " id=3D"section-step-2-find-the-median-of-the-lower-half-of-the-data"=
>Step 2 - Find the median of the lower half of the data
</h4><p class=3D"text-grey col-span-10 md:col-span-8 lg:col-span-6 md:col-s=
tart-2 lg:col-start-3">The median divides your set of data into two equal p=
arts: a lower half and an upper half. You can calculate the first quartile =
(Q1), by finding the median of the lower half of the data.
</p><h4 class=3D"
       =20
       =20
       =20
        font-light text-[20px] leading-[27px] md:text-[27px] md:leading-[36=
px]
       =20
        col-span-10 md:col-span-8 lg:col-span-6 md:col-start-2 lg:col-start=
-3
      " id=3D"section-step-3-find-the-median-of-the-upper-half-of-the-data"=
>Step 3 - Find the median of the upper half of the data
</h4><p class=3D"text-grey col-span-10 md:col-span-8 lg:col-span-6 md:col-s=
tart-2 lg:col-start-3">You can calculate the upper quartile (Q3) by finding=
 the median of the upper half of your data.=20
</p><h3 class=3D"
