king at a list of quartiles, a boxplot, or a box and whisker plot, always r=
emember what each quartile represents.

</p><ol class=3D"list-decimal col-span-10 md:col-span-8 lg:col-span-6 md:co=
l-start-2 lg:col-start-3 pl-[24px]"><li class=3D"text-grey"><p class=3D"tex=
t-grey col-span-10 md:col-span-8 lg:col-span-6 md:col-start-2 lg:col-start-=
3">Q1 marks the 25th percentile of your data and divides the bottom quarter=
 of your data from the second quarter. </p></li><li class=3D"text-grey"><p =
class=3D"text-grey col-span-10 md:col-span-8 lg:col-span-6 md:col-start-2 l=
g:col-start-3">
Q2 marks the 50th percentile (the median) of your data and divides the seco=
nd quarter of your data from the third quarter. </p></li><li class=3D"text-=
grey"><p class=3D"text-grey col-span-10 md:col-span-8 lg:col-span-6 md:col-=
start-2 lg:col-start-3">
Q3 marks the 75th percentile of your data and divides the third quarter of =
your data points from the top quarter. </p></li><li class=3D"text-grey"><p =
class=3D"text-grey col-span-10 md:col-span-8 lg:col-span-6 md:col-start-2 l=
g:col-start-3">
Subtracting Q3 from Q1 will give you the interquartile range (IQR). The IQR=
 tells you how dispersed the middle 50 percent of your data is.
</p></li></ol><h2 class=3D"
